03968nam a22005295i 9780773563414DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19921992xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735634147 a10.1515/97807735634142doi  a(DE-B1597)655467  a(OCoLC)1109365651  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHN445.5 ǂb K47 1992eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306/.09431 aGlatzer, Wolfgang, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRecent Social Trends in West Germany, 1960-1990 /cWolfgang Glatzer, Karl Otto Hondrich. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1992] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (564 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative Charting of Social Change ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tContext -- tAge Groups -- tMicrosocial -- tWomen -- tLabour Market -- tLabour and Management -- tSocial Stratification -- tSocial Relations -- tState and Service Institutions -- tMobilizing Institutions -- tInstitutionalization of Social Forces -- tIdeologies -- tHousehold Resources -- tLife Style -- tLeisure -- tEducational Attainment -- tIntegration and Marginalization -- tAttitudes and Values -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe thirty-year period examined was characterized in West Germany by a number of inconsistent trends. While income and consumption levels increased as part of a "silent revolution," poverty also increased, especially during the 1980s. People's lifestyles changed, with less time spent on formal employment and more on household production and recreation. Individualization and pluralization began to dissolve the class structure, and social movements such as feminism and environmentalism gained some influence. Although hostility toward foreigners did not disappear, de facto immigrants were increasingly integrated into society. Satisfaction with life reached a generally high and stable level, although some people expressed an unanticipated degree of boredom. The legitimacy of the political system was not affected by conflicts about income distribution and changing values, and cooperation grew among government, business, and traditional and emerging intermediate groups. Special chapters have been authored by Johann Behrens, Mathias Bös, Bernhard Engel, Renate Hornung-Draus, Heiner Meulemann, Claudia Koch-Arzberger, Jürgen Kohl, Jakob Schissler, Jürgen Schumacher, and Karin Seibel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aHondrich, Karl Otto, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356341440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773563414423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773563414/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles